featured_reviews.review_id:
It's a must visit place if you're in Nainital. It's so beautiful and mesmerising situated between mountains  and on side of Naini lake. Very easy to get darshan on most of the days without any hassle.

Standing on one side of the beautiful Naini Lake is the Naina Devi Temple, which is a famous Indian pilgrimage and one of the 51 Shaktipeeths in India. Located on the banks of the lake, it is a beautiful tourist destination as well.

Naina Devi Temple History:
Built in 15th AD, Naina Devi temple idol was installed by a devotee Moti Ram Shah in 1842. After a drastic landslides in 1880, Naina Devi temple was completely destroyed. Soon in 1883 locals build again the Naina Devi Temple since they have deep faith on Maa Naina Devi.

The Naina Devi temple mythology:

The Naina Devi temple gets its name from the mythological legend that Goddess Sati's eyes (Nayan) fell at this place when Lord Vishnu cuts her body into 51 different parts. In fact, the whole town (Nainital), the lake (Naini Lake) and the Naini temple, all three of them are named after the legend.

Naina devi temple entry and timing:

1. No Entry Fee
2. Timing  : 6am to 10 pm on most of the days of year
3. Arti Timing: 7 am in morning and 7 pm in the evening
4. Naina Devi Temple Nainital Address: Ayarpatta, Near Naini Lake, Nainital, Uttarakhand, 263002, India

How to reach:

The temple is located at the Northern end of the Naini Lake in the Mallital area.

Roadways- It is located at a distance of 3 km from the Nainital city bus stand. You can easily walk to the temple or hire a local rickshaw or auto rickshaw.

Railways-The temple is 35 km from the nearest railway station which is Kathgodam Railway station. You can hire a taxi cab from the railway station to reach the temple.

Airways- The temple is located 55 km away from the Pantnagar Airport. Once off the flight, you can hire a local taxi cab to reach the temple.

Private  Vehicle (car): You can park your car  in public parking in central area near to gurudwara and everything is easy accessible on foot from there.

featured_reviews.review_translated_text:
The city of Nainital in Uttarakhand offers its guests a lot of places of interest for travelers and visiting these attractions is a real pleasure. Naina Devi Temple is one of the main tourist attractions of Nainital and is a highly revered place for pilgrims. The lake area in Nainital is where all the main attractions of the city are found.

Naina Devi Temple is situated on the top of Naina Hill on the northern bank of Naini Lake in Nainital, Uttarakhand. The main deity of the temple is Maa Naina Devi who is represented by two Netra or eyes. Nainital is one of the 64 Shaktipeeths also known as religious places of Hinduism.

In the olden days of history when Lord Shiva's wife Sati, unable to accept the insult by her father King Daksha for refusing to invite Sati and Lord Shiva to the Yagya, she burnt herself in the fire. Devastated and suffering from grief, when Lord Shiva was returning to his abode with her body in his arms, her body parts fell at various places on earth. The temple of Naina Devi is built at the place where the eyes (Naina) of the goddess are believed to have fallen when Lord Shiva was carrying her body.

A very old temple believed to be built in the 15th century AD was rebuilt in 1883. Behind the temple there is a lake 167 yards wide and 93 feet deep. There is a huge Peepal tree on the left side of the temple gate. On the right side, there are idols of Lord Hanuman and Lord Ganesha. The 3 deities inside the temple are Maa Kali Devi, Maa Naina Devi and Lord Ganesha. Since 1918-19, every year on Bhadrapada Shukla Ashtami, the idol immersion ceremony is performed here, similar to the idol immersion ceremony celebrated in Maharashtra and West Bengal.

With its stunning architecture, panoramic views, and religious significance, the temple is a testament to the country's deep-rooted traditions and spirituality. You'll get mental peace and positivity here.
Devotees from all over the country come to the temple to seek blessings from the goddess Naina Devi, who is believed to bestow her blessings on those who pray with a pure heart.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Very nice temple away from all the hassle and market and commercialisation. it's a quiet place and a temple at almost end of the lake. You have to walk on side of Naini lake that is also good experience and once you reach near to end of naini lake, Pashan devi temple is there.

Pashan Devi is worshipped as a representation of the Nav Durga or Nine incarnations of Goddess Durga. The temple is a complete stone structure and the Goddess is also worshipped in stone form.

Pashan Devi is one of the oldest regional temples in Nainital and holds great significance importance in enhancing the culture of the place.

An eternal flame or Akhand Jyoti is lit at the temple since its formation. Water is offered to the Nave Durga at the temple by the devotees which flows into the Naini lake after touching the feet of the Goddess. Clothes and Sindoor are also offered to the Goddess at the temple.

Opening hours: 6am -7:30 pam Monday to Sunday

Entry: Entry free

Pashan Devi Temple Nainital Address: Tallital, Nainital, Uttarakhand, 263002, India

On the hillock adjacent to the road on the right side near the mid point of Naini Lake, there is another important goddess temple called Pashan Devi Temple. At this place established in the form of Navadurga, the figures of 9 forms of Mother Bhagwati are incarnated on stone. Lakhs of devotees come here from far and wide to offer prayers.
It is difficult to find evidence as to when this temple was built here. It is said that the temple of Pashan Devi is present at this place since the time of origin of Nainijheel and nine incarnations of Goddess Bhagwati are being worshiped since then. Devotees coming here offer vermillion to the goddess and the idol of the goddess is decorated with vermillion.

featured_reviews.review_translated_text:
There are many such temples in Devbhoomi Uttarakhand, where the wishes of children are fulfilled. Today we are going to tell you about one such temple located in Padampuri of Nainital district. An ancient temple of Pashan Devi (Pashan Devi Temple in Nainital) is situated on the top of the mountain. This temple is built inside a cave. This temple situated at an altitude of about 1800 to 2000 meters has many beliefs. It is believed that just by seeing the goddess in this temple one gets the happiness of children.
Years ago, when a woman was going from the mountain towards Bhabhar with her child, then suddenly her child fell into the ditch from the place of that temple. When Pashan Devi appeared in the woman's dream at night, she told that her child was safe in the village of Chafi below and the next day the woman found her child. Since then the importance of this temple has increased even more.

featured_reviews.review_id:
Ever dreamt of an almost infinite water body surrounded by lush green mountains, pleasantly chilly breeze, chirping birds, colorful boats, mixed flora and orange-colored common carp fish looking at you from beneath the water? You must have been standing at the Naini Lake in your dream.

Snuggled amidst the beautiful Kumaon town of Nainital, the Naini lake is nothing less than fresh out of dreams. The crescent-shaped freshwater lake is a popular tourist destination throughout the year. The lake is surrounded by snowy peaks at the north, Tiffin point at the south-west and Naini peak (after which the town and the lake are named) at the North-west.

The destination is an all time favorite for families, friends, honeymooners and among those on one-day tours. It offers you a splendid experience of enjoying its beauty while having a stroll across its boundary, boating in the shimmering waters, and quacking with the joyous ducks.

featured_reviews.review_id:
This natural freshwater lake beauty is charming and many world's prominent writers explained its beauty in words of their poems. Inspiring Naini Lake has also attracted many writers and creative personalities towards it.

Nainital is also named after Naini Lake which covers a perimeter of 2 miles with a depth from 28 metres to 6 metres. Still water of Naini Lake makes visitors to fall in love with its alluring beauty. This lake was found long back in 1839 by P.Baron a British businessman who came across this lake on a hunting expedition.Naini Lake topology has two parts namely Mallital and Tallital. Northern part is called as Mallital while Southern part known as Tallital. Nainital visit can't be complete without a boat ride in the lake. Visitors love to explore scintillating lake on boat provided by Nainital boat club. Tourist finds ample opportunity for shopping near Nainital Lake on famous Mall Road.

Boating in Nainital is a delightful experience that allows visitors to immerse themselves in the serene beauty of this picturesque hill station located in Uttarakhand, India. Here is a review highlighting the key aspects of boating in Nainital.

The star attraction of Nainital is its stunning lake, aptly named Naini Lake. The lake's calm waters and surrounding hills create a mesmerizing setting for boating enthusiasts. The boating experience here is both peaceful and enchanting, offering a unique perspective of the town and its scenic surroundings.
